        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria — power-law hemolysis model with documented uncertainty",
        "description": "The power-law hemolysis damage model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) must be used with explicitly documented low confidence in the model-form coefficients. Wide uncertainty bounds on predicted NIH arising from coefficient uncertainty must be quantified via Monte Carlo and reported. Acceptance requires that the 95% CI upper bound on NIH remains below the clinical threshold even under pessimistic coefficient assumptions."
      },
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is employed. It is explicitly acknowledged that the model-form coefficients (alpha, beta, C) carry low confidence: literature values span nearly an order of magnitude, and the coefficients were fit to bovine blood data that may not fully represent the COU fluid. Monte Carlo sampling over the published coefficient range yields a 95% CI on NIH of [0.012, 0.071] g/100L at the worst-case operating point, compared to a clinical threshold of 0.1 g/100L. The upper bound of the CI (0.071) remains below the threshold with a margin of 29%, and the central estimate (0.031) is well within acceptance. This low-confidence limitation is documented honestly and accepted as residual risk; the safety margin is judged sufficient given the conservative coefficient sampling. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
